IFECHI OKOH Some members of Musical Society Copyright of Nigeria (MCSN) who have released works in the market are alleged to be crossed with the Association’s liberal policy of extending their sharing to artistes yet to have albums. Some of the aggrieved members who claimed they have attended MCSN copyright seminar over the years, maintained that the MCSN Liberal policy is actually against the constitution which does not make provision for artistes yet to release any work. ‘Apes Obey,’ Story Of A Lagos Where Whites Never Mixed With The… Who Is After Demola Seriki? One of the vexed feelers (members) informed that the royalty is usually shared into two parts, insisting that 70% goes to artiste members who have released works, while the remaining 30% is shared among production personnel, distributors, back-up (Chorus Singers) and dancers. The feeler based his information on over two decades seminar attended, urging artistes to endeavour to attend copyright seminars, so as to be educated on the going-on in the MCSN and also participate actively, regularly to acquaint themselves with the rules and regulations of the association, thereby protecting their interest as expected.